<paragraph blockId="13.[351,556,1523,1581]" box="[355,553,1523,1549]" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hay" authorityYear="1929" box="[355,482,1523,1549]" class="Actinopterygii" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Amiiformes</taxonomicName>
indet.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="694" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[351,556,1523,1581]" box="[351,556,1554,1581]" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">
(
<figureCitation box="[360,423,1554,1581]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="12.[132,143,1340,1357]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1298]" captionTargetId="figure-292@12.[132,1455,215,1298]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIG. 7. — Actinopterygian remains from Angeac-Charente: A, B, isolated tooth of Ginglymodi indet. (ANG M-30) in anterior/posterior (A) and occlusal (B) views; C, Ginglymodi indet. scale (ANG M-68); D, Ginglymodi indet. scale (ANG M-67); E, upper jaw fragment of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-62) in lingual view; F, left dentary of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-117) in labial view; G, H, fragmentary left dentary of Amiiformes (ANG 15-4062) in lingual (G) and labial (H) views. Scale bar represents: A, B, 1 mm; C, 4 mm; D, 2 mm; E, 2.5 mm; F, 10 mm; G, H, 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902049/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Figs 7</figureCitation>
E-H; 8A-D)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[130,777,1619,2028]" box="[132,277,1619,1645]" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[130,777,1619,2028]" lastBlockId="13.[812,1457,1395,1613]" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">
Amiiform fish are represented in the assemblage by isolated teeth, jaw remains (
<figureCitation box="[351,415,1682,1709]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="12.[132,143,1340,1357]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1298]" captionTargetId="figure-292@12.[132,1455,215,1298]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIG. 7. — Actinopterygian remains from Angeac-Charente: A, B, isolated tooth of Ginglymodi indet. (ANG M-30) in anterior/posterior (A) and occlusal (B) views; C, Ginglymodi indet. scale (ANG M-68); D, Ginglymodi indet. scale (ANG M-67); E, upper jaw fragment of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-62) in lingual view; F, left dentary of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-117) in labial view; G, H, fragmentary left dentary of Amiiformes (ANG 15-4062) in lingual (G) and labial (H) views. Scale bar represents: A, B, 1 mm; C, 4 mm; D, 2 mm; E, 2.5 mm; F, 10 mm; G, H, 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902049/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
E-H) and vertebrae. Most of the labiolingually compressed teeth show a typical triangular crown apex and bear two well-developed carinae (
<figureCitation box="[592,653,1746,1772]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="13.[132,143,1265,1282]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1222]" captionTargetId="figure-294@13.[132,1455,215,1222]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIG. 8. — Actinopterygian remains from the Berriasian of Angeac-Charente:A, isolated tooth of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-39); B, C, isolated tooth of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-110); D, dentulous vomerine element of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-56); E-G, isolated tooth of Ionoscopiformes indet. (ANG M-111); H, jaw frag- ment of Actinopterygii indet. (ANG M-38) in lingual view; I, vertebra of Actinopterygii indet. (ANG M-069). Scale bar: A-C, E-H, 500 µm; D, 250 µm; I, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902051/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
A-C). Such teeth were previously referred to 
<taxonomicName box="[476,596,1778,1804]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Moraceae" genus="Caturus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[476,559,1778,1804]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Caturus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="SWEETMAN S. C. &amp; GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M." journalOrPublisher="Biological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" pagination="872 - 896" part="113" refId="ref49895" refString="SWEETMAN S. C., GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M. 2014. - A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 113: 872 - 896. https: // doi. org / 10.4202 / app. 2011.0109" title="A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England" type="journal article" year="2014">
Sweetman 
<emphasis box="[725,775,1778,1804]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="VULLO R. &amp; ABIT D. &amp; BALLEVRE M. &amp; BILLON- BRUYAT J. - P. &amp; BOURGEAIS R. &amp; BUFFETAUT E. &amp; DAVIERO- GOMEZ V. &amp; GARCIA G. &amp; GOMEZ B. &amp; MAZIN J. - M. &amp; MOREL S. &amp; NERAUDEAU D. &amp; POUECH J. &amp; RAGE J. - C. &amp; SCHNYDER J. &amp; TONG H." box="[203,387,1810,1836]" journalOrPublisher="Comptes Rendus Palevol" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" pagination="421 - 441" part="13" refId="ref50388" refString="VULLO R., ABIT D., BALLEVRE M., BILLON- BRUYAT J. - P., BOURGEAIS R., BUFFETAUT E., DAVIERO- GOMEZ V., GARCIA G., GOMEZ B., MAZIN J. - M., MOREL S., NERAUDEAU D., POUECH J., RAGE J. - C., SCHNYDER J. &amp; TONG H. 2014. - Palaeontology of the Purbeck-type (Tithonian, Late Jurassic) bonebeds of Chassiron (Oleron Island, western France). Comptes Rendus Palevol 13: 421 - 441. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. crpv. 2014.03.003" title="Palaeontology of the Purbeck-type (Tithonian, Late Jurassic) bonebeds of Chassiron (Oleron Island, western France)" type="journal article" year="2014">
Vullo 
<emphasis box="[270,323,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="POUECH J. &amp; MAZIN J. - M. &amp; CAVIN L. &amp; POYATO- ARIZA F. J." box="[403,606,1809,1836]" journalOrPublisher="Cretaceous Research" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" pagination="32 - 43" part="55" refId="ref46928" refString="POUECH J., MAZIN J. - M., CAVIN L., POYATO- ARIZA F. J. 2015. - A Berriasian actinopterygians fauna from Cherves-de-Cognac, France: biodiversity and palaeoenvironmental implications. Cretaceous Research 55: 32 - 43. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2015.01.001" title="A Berriasian actinopterygians fauna from Cherves-de-Cognac, France: biodiversity and palaeoenvironmental implications" type="journal article" year="2015">
Pouech 
<emphasis box="[490,543,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
), although this dental morphology is also present in more derived members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hay" authorityYear="1929" box="[162,289,1873,1899]" class="Actinopterygii" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Amiiformes</taxonomicName>
(i.e., 
<taxonomicName box="[356,452,1873,1900]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Amiidae</taxonomicName>
). Some tooth associations are interpreted as vomerine dentitions (
<figureCitation box="[511,595,1905,1932]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="13.[132,143,1265,1282]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1222]" captionTargetId="figure-294@13.[132,1455,215,1222]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIG. 8. — Actinopterygian remains from the Berriasian of Angeac-Charente:A, isolated tooth of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-39); B, C, isolated tooth of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-110); D, dentulous vomerine element of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-56); E-G, isolated tooth of Ionoscopiformes indet. (ANG M-111); H, jaw frag- ment of Actinopterygii indet. (ANG M-38) in lingual view; I, vertebra of Actinopterygii indet. (ANG M-069). Scale bar: A-C, E-H, 500 µm; D, 250 µm; I, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902051/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
). These elements bear teeth of various sizes, subconical and devoid of carinae, as those found in many 
<taxonomicName authority="(Grande &amp; Bemis 1998)" baseAuthorityName="Grande &amp; Bemis" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[380,770,1969,1996]" class="Actinopterygii" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">
Amiiformes (
<bibRefCitation author="Grande &amp; Bemis" box="[520,759,1969,1995]" firstAuthor="Grande" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" pagination="1 - 696" refId="ref40685" refString="GRANDE L. &amp; BEMIS W. E. 1998. - A comprehensive phylogenetic study of amiid fishes (Amiidae) based on comparative skeletal anatomy. An empirical search for interconnected patterns of natural history. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 18 (suppl. 1): 1 - 696." type="journal article" year="1998">Grande &amp; Bemis 1998</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It is worth noting that this tooth morphology corresponds to that usually assigned to the aspidorhynchid 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agassiz" authorityYear="1834" box="[1318,1456,1395,1421]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aspidorhynchidae" genus="Belonostomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1318,1456,1395,1421]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Belonostomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="SWEETMAN S. C. &amp; GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M." box="[874,1110,1427,1453]" journalOrPublisher="Biological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" pagination="872 - 896" part="113" refId="ref49895" refString="SWEETMAN S. C., GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M. 2014. - A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 113: 872 - 896. https: // doi. org / 10.4202 / app. 2011.0109" title="A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England" type="journal article" year="2014">
Sweetman 
<emphasis box="[993,1046,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="POUECH J. &amp; MAZIN J. - M. &amp; CAVIN L. &amp; POYATO- ARIZA F. J." box="[1125,1328,1427,1454]" journalOrPublisher="Cretaceous Research" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" pagination="32 - 43" part="55" refId="ref46928" refString="POUECH J., MAZIN J. - M., CAVIN L., POYATO- ARIZA F. J. 2015. - A Berriasian actinopterygians fauna from Cherves-de-Cognac, France: biodiversity and palaeoenvironmental implications. Cretaceous Research 55: 32 - 43. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2015.01.001" title="A Berriasian actinopterygians fauna from Cherves-de-Cognac, France: biodiversity and palaeoenvironmental implications" type="journal article" year="2015">
Pouech 
<emphasis box="[1212,1265,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). However, the rounded morphology of the vomerine tooth plates from Angeac-Charente and the fact that they are paired elements preclude assignment to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agassiz" authorityYear="1834" box="[1068,1206,1523,1549]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aspidorhynchidae" genus="Belonostomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1068,1206,1523,1549]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Belonostomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in which the vomer is unpaired); therefore, all isolated small teeth with a conical crown devoid of carinae are here referred to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Grande &amp; Bemis" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[1265,1390,1586,1612]" class="Actinopterygii" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Amiiformes</taxonomicName>
indet.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
